    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/08-agents-harness/03-harness-coding-agent.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The harness is deterministic code wrapping a stochastic model; with a fixed model, the harness is what converts raw skill into a verified change in a real repo.; Models are stateless across calls; continuity is manufactured by re-serializing the entire transcript every turn, which is why the static preamble is kept byte-stable (prefix caching) and tool outputs must be truncated.; The agent loop is reason -> act -> observe, with STRUCTURAL termination (stop exactly when the assistant emits no tool call) and errors treated as first-class observations that feed back, not exceptions that crash.; Verification in the loop is the single biggest quality lever: a strong harness bounces every edit off a ground-truth oracle (test/build/lint) and refuses to finish until it passes; plausibility is not correctness.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  edit-tool-unique-match-contract\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
