    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/09-rag-retrieval/01-embeddings-representation.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Dense retrieval beats keyword matching because it maps meaning to geometry: 'car' and 'automobile' land close in vector space even with zero word overlap, whereas sparse/BM25 vectors are near-orthogonal.; The bi-encoder's power is INDEPENDENCE: query and document are encoded separately, so every document vector is precomputed offline and only the query is embedded at query time (cross-encoders can't do this).; InfoNCE turns a batch into a classification problem: a B x B similarity matrix whose diagonal are the true (query, positive) pairs and whose off-diagonal cells are free in-batch negatives; a row-wise softmax (sharpened by temperature) must pick the diagonal.; Contrastive training reshapes the space: it pulls each query toward its positive and pushes negatives away, converting an anisotropic cone of embeddings into a spread-out isotropic sphere; HARD negatives (superficially similar) provide far more signal than random ones.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  emb-dense-vs-sparse-vocab-mismatch\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
