    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/09-rag-retrieval/06-multimodal-visual-retrieval.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The single-vector information bottleneck: CLIP/SigLIP crush an entire dense page (dozens of distinct facts) into ONE vector, so a specific query cannot latch onto the one fact that answers it. This failure is the whole motivation for late interaction.; The retrieval-interaction spectrum: cross-encoder (joint attention, maximally expressive, too slow to scan) vs bi-encoder (one vector per side, fast but lossy) vs late interaction (token/patch vectors + cheap MaxSim at the end) as the middle path that keeps granularity AND precomputability.; MaxSim as an operation, not a formula: each query token scans ALL document patches, keeps only its single best match (row-max of the query-by-patch similarity grid), and the page score is the sum of those best matches. There is NO query-page cross-attention; the only interaction is these dot products at the very end.; ColPali's one clean move: replace ColBERT's BERT-token document encoder with a VLM that turns a page IMAGE into a grid of ~1024 contextualized patch vectors, so a query token for 'revenue' can match the patch rendering 'Revenue: 4.2B' with no OCR ever run.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  multivector-storage-funnel\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
