    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/11-evaluation/01-eval-landscape.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Every eval is a chain of proxies: each hop from 'is this model useful?' down to 'cross-entropy on the next token' leaks a bit of validity, so the number you read is several proxies removed from what you care about.; A good evaluator must be valid, reliable, and sensitive at once; real benchmarks routinely fail at least one, and knowing which one is failing tells you how to read the score.; Benchmark scores carry sampling noise: SE = sqrt(p(1-p)/n), so sub-1% gaps on MMLU-sized sets sit inside overlapping confidence intervals and are not real differences.; A score is only informative inside a band (~20-80%): a result far below random chance means a broken answer extractor rather than a weak model, and a result above ~80% means saturation where question quality, not capability, drives the number.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  contamination-severity-gradient\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
