    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/12-production-mlops/05-data-flywheel.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The flywheel is a self-reinforcing loop whose returns COMPOUND: better data -> better model -> more users -> denser, sharper-tail signal -> better data. After k rounds an incumbent's training distribution covers a long tail no static dataset can match, and this distribution gap \u2014 not the model architecture \u2014 is the moat a new entrant cannot close.; Explicit human preference (thumbs) is scarce and high-quality (a few percent of traffic); implicit behavioral signals (copy, edit, regenerate, session continuation) are abundant but noisy. A proxy reward model trained to predict explicit thumbs from implicit signals extends usable labels from that few-percent tip to ~100% of traffic.; Active learning gets far more model improvement per label by choosing WHICH examples to annotate: uncertainty (low per-token logprob) finds where the model struggles, but uncertainty alone over-samples one redundant cluster \u2014 a diversity / core-set constraint spreads the budget across the hard tail so each label buys new coverage.; Client feedback signals arrive seconds-to-minutes AFTER the request, so an immutable log record must be enriched later by a session-windowed streaming join keyed on request_id; records with no signal are not wasted \u2014 they carry implicit weak-supervision labels.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  compounding-flywheel-moat\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
