    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/99-appendix/05-from-scratch-index.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The from-scratch implementations form a bottom-up dependency arc: math primitives (autograd) are the root, everything downstream is a specialization of 'forward builds a graph, backward traverses it'.; One shared stack carries two distinct flows: the forward/inference path (text -> tokens -> embeddings -> blocks -> logits -> sampled token) and the training/gradient path (loss -> autograd -> LoRA-restricted updates -> alignment objectives).; Components are swappable modules with fixed interfaces: BPE<->unigram, sinusoidal<->RoPE, dense attention<->FlashAttention, so the same skeleton supports many concrete choices.; The book's learning arc is organized in tiers by role (foundations -> transformer -> post-training -> hardware kernels -> inference-time algorithms); reading them in order is a complete construction of an LLM system.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  fsindex-learning-arc-tiers\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
